    "Restricting to the invertible part D (X) volume of O 2 past a junction topological local operator D (g) 0.1 = D (h) 1 for h ∈ H C, we O 2 D (τ(g)) 1 D (X) 1 D (g) d-2 D (g) 0 = O 2 D (τ(g)) 1 D (X) 1 D (g) d-2 D (X) 1 ⊗ D (τ(g)) 1 ⊗ D (X *) 1 D (g) 0learn that the image of the homomorphism (76) is contained in the center Z(H C) of H C. That is, induced 1-form symmetries can only source localized symmetries lying in Z(H C).The action of the H C localized 0-form symmetry ish ∈ H C: D (g) 0 → φ g (h)D (g) 0,(80)where φ g (h) ∈ × such thatφ g (h)φ g (h ′) = φ g (hh ′), φ g (1) = 1.",
    "(81)This means that the junction topological local operator D (g) 0 furnishes a 1-dimensional representation of H C. Thus we have an homomorphismφ: G (1) → χ(H C), (82)where χ(H C) is the character group, namely the group formed by 1-dimensional representations, of H C. The action of H C on induced 1-form symmetries can be viewed as a mixed 't Hooft anomaly between the localized 0-form and the induced 1-form symmetries of the formA 3 = φ B 2 | O 2 (A 1), (83)where the notation for background fields has been discussed above.",
    "More concretely, A 3 is a × valued 3-cocycle whose explicit simplicial form isA 3 (v 0, v 1, v 2, v 3) = φ B 2 | O 2 (v 0,v 1,v 2) (A 1 (v 2, v 3)) ∈ ×, (84)where v i are vertices in a simplicial decomposition,B 2 | O 2 (v 0, v 1, v 2) ∈ G (1) and A 1 (v 2, v 3) ∈ H C.Note that, for consistency we must demand thatδA 3 = 0,(85)which is a non-trivial condition to satisfy due to the non-closure condition (78).",
    "Later, in example 3.2, we will describe a surface operator (called O 2 there) in the pure 4d O(4N) gauge theory exhibiting 2 0-form localized symmetry under which the topological local operator generating 2 1-form symmetry induced from the 4d bulk is non-trivially charged.",
    "'t Hooft anomaly for induced 1-form symmetry."
